column40: The single plate was discovered in a field at Rawan and was in private possession for about 15 years. Afterwards, it was purchased and preserved in the Rānī Durgāvatī Museum at Jabalpur.

At some point before 1957, when the single copperplate was first published, it was discovered while digging a plot of land at Pokhra as part of a set complete with ring. Due to a quarrel between the diggers, the decision was made to divide the set and only the present plate survived (whereas the rest of the set was melted down). Afterwards, it was preserved in the possession of an inhabitant of Rājim.
At some point in the nineteen seventies, the single plate was found at Būrhīkhār by a man named Pandey, whose family has preserved the plate ever since.
At some point before 1995, when the single copperplate was first published, it was found in the possession of a school teacher at Būrhīkhār.
